In this notebook, I will write some notes about how to make data visualisations in R using the miles per gallon dataset.

We can find this dataset by typing mpg after importing the ggplot2 package.

mpg

To create a plot call ggplot, pass the dataframe that will be used and then map things accordingly after specifying the geom envrionment.

ggplot(data=mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x=displ, y= hwy))

If you run ggplot on its own you get an empty space.

ggplot(data=mpg)

Not very interesting

We can get the number of column and rows of a dataset by using the nrow and ncol functions.

ncol(mpg)
## [1] 11
nrow(mpg)
## [1] 234

So, using the logic from above, we can get a scatter plot of the hwy and cyl variables like so.

ggplot(data=mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x=hwy, y=cyl))

ggplot(data=mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x=class, y=drv))

Obviously, this plot isnt very useful because we are looking at two categorical variables. The points are just telling us that these observations exist, but tells us nothing more about these points.

We can color the points using the aesthetic function inside of the geoms:

ggplot(data=mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=displ, y=hwy, color=class))

We can how see where the different classifications of cars are concentrated in this graph. The colors are all mapped automatically for us which saves us having to write something like a for-loop like we might for other visualisation packages.

Note that we can use other mappings such as alpha and shape parameters

ggplot(data=mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=displ, y=hwy, alpha=class))
## Warning: Using alpha for a discrete variable is not advised.

Luckily, we get a warning that using a categorical variable inside of alpha is likely an idea that doesnt make much sense.

ggplot(data=mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=displ, y=hwy, shape=class))
## Warning: The shape palette can deal with a maximum of 6 discrete values because
## more than 6 becomes difficult to discriminate; you have 7. Consider
## specifying shapes manually if you must have them.
## Warning: Removed 62 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

We can see here that we only have 6 shapes that we can choose from, so using the shape parameter here isnt so great either.

Note as well that continuous variables cannot be mapped using shapes.

Ofcourse, settings can also be chosen manually by placing them outside of the aesthetics function

ggplot(data=mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=displ, y=hwy), colour="blue")

Note that if you try and define the color inside of the aesthetics function, it will interpret it as being one class and give it the red color. You can wrap the string in an I() function, but its probably just best to assign these things outside of the aes in the first place.

Facets

Sometimes you want to plot multiple variables at a time, facets are good for this.

ggplot(data=mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=displ, y=hwy)) + 
  facet_wrap(~class, nrow=2)

Here, we were able to take the above graph and split it apart by the car class, which can sometimes be handy.

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_grid(drv ~ cyl)

Heres a question, what happens if you facet on a continuous variable

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_grid( ~ cty)

It seems like it kind of works.

Note that faceting and using aesthetics have different functions. You might use faceting if you want to have everything in one place to make comparisons between things more apparent, faceting separates the effects out so you can investigate more inside of a single plot without having to faff around with filtering things.

Geometric Objects

Note that the geom associated with a plot decides how the plot is going to be formed.

# left
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))

# right
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

Here, we get two plots, but one is some kind of a model that helps us to see the underlying trend in the data, we can also combine these plots together as follows.

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))+   # left
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))  # right
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

It seems like this model is overfitting to the data a little bit. The couple of points above seem to be drawing the line further up than would probably make sense.

Note that we can also map the smoothing function to things like what kind of a drive the car is.

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +  
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color=drv, linetype=drv))   
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

Note that you can also create separate lines using the group aesthetic. Itll perform the same function as when you use the color aesthetic, only the lines wont be colored. Shocker!

This line is overfit even more because the model that is used to fit the data is very flexible but we dont have enough points to justify using something so flexible, except maybe for four wheel drive cars, there the model seems to fit a little better.

If you ever want to hide a legend, you can pass a show.legend parameter

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +  
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color=drv, linetype=drv), show.legend = FALSE) 
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

Thats quite useful to know!

Note that above we have some duplication when we combined the points geom with the smooth geom, what if there were a way to program this all together

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

Anything thats defined in the aesthetics section of the parent ggplot will be passed to all of the geoms as well.

You can even extend what was set by default by further specifying things inside of the geoms.

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color=class)) + 
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

You can even specify which points to filter for.

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color=class)) + 
  geom_smooth(data=filter(mpg, class!="2seater"), se=FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

Here, our smooth geom is ignoring the 2 seaters which were annoying from before, I think I might also ignore displ that are higher than 6.

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color=class)) + 
  geom_smooth(data=filter(mpg, class!="2seater", displ<6), se=FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

Note that the se parameter dictates whether loess smoothing comes with a confidence interval.

We can also change it so that it does a linear regression.

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color=class)) + 
  geom_smooth(data=filter(mpg, class!="2seater", displ<6), method='lm')

Statistical Transformations

Consider the diamonds dataset, we can use a barplot to get the count of each kind of cut

ggplot(data=diamonds) + 
  geom_bar(mapping=aes(x=cut))

Something interesting just happened here, though! There is no count variable in the diamonds dataset, so what happened here?

  • Bar charts, histograms, and freq polygons automatically bin the data and plot the counts
  • Smoothers fit a model to the data and then plot that fit
  • boxplots compute a summary of the distribution and then plot that

Note that the statistic that is calculated can also be changed using the stat parameter.

You can create the same plot like so

ggplot(data=diamonds) + 
  stat_count(mapping=aes(x=cut))

This works because the default stat for the bar plot is count!

Heres a difficulty though, what is the statistics have already been calculated?

demo <- tribble(
  ~cut,         ~freq,
  "Fair",       1610,
  "Good",       4906,
  "Very Good",  12082,
  "Premium",    13791,
  "Ideal",      21551
)

demo
## # A tibble: 5 x 2
##   cut        freq
##   <chr>     <dbl>
## 1 Fair       1610
## 2 Good       4906
## 3 Very Good 12082
## 4 Premium   13791
## 5 Ideal     21551
ggplot(data=demo) + 
  geom_bar(mapping=aes(x=cut, y=freq), stat="identity")

Note that you need the identity stat because the stat that is being used is the value itself.

We can also do something like calculating the percent of total

tot <- sum(demo$freq)
demo$perc.tot <- demo$freq/tot

ggplot(data=demo) + 
  geom_bar(mapping=aes(x=cut, y=perc.tot), stat="identity")

You can do a similar kind of thing using the diamonds dataset except without the explicit calculation.

ggplot(data=diamonds) + 
  geom_bar(mapping=aes(x=cut, y=stat(prop), group=1))

Im not exactly sure why we are using group = 1 and why that gives the same thing when we equate it to two. I guess it means that it treats all things inside of this vis as a group and then calculates the proporitons on that. If we remove the group function then the proportion is always equal to one, as it groups by the cut.

It should also be noted that you can also get geom_col which requires that you pass whatever you are plotting on the y axis manually.

You can also do more sophisticated things

ggplot(data=diamonds) + 
  stat_summary(
    mapping=aes(x=cut, y=depth),
    fun.ymin=min,
    fun.ymax=max,
    fun.y=median
  )

Note that ggplot has over 20 stats that can be used, each of which is a function. So you can use the ?stat_bin function in order to have a look at all of them.

Position Adjustments

You can also create barplots which are unstacked using colour vs fill.

ggplot(data=diamonds) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x=cut, fill=cut))

ggplot(data=diamonds) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x=cut, fill=clarity))

The differnce here is the position parameter. This parameter can be filled with identity, dodge and fill.

ggplot(data=diamonds) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x=cut, fill=clarity), position = "dodge")

ggplot(data=diamonds) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x=cut, fill=clarity), position = "fill")

So, using this we can get different kinds of batplot, which is handy.

There is also a jitter position for scatterplots:

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy), position = "jitter")

This can be useful to avoid overplotting in some cases, for instance.

Coordinate Systems

You can also flip a graph by using the coord_flip() geom

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = class, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_boxplot() +
  coord_flip()
